<DOC><DOCNO> AP900226-0202 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-90 2138EST</FILEID><FIRST>a e BC-WKD--EntertainmentBriefs Adv00   02-26 0223</FIRST><SECOND>BC-WKD--Entertainment Briefs, Adv 00,0229</SECOND><NOTE>$adv00</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE><HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD><HEAD>Entertainment Briefs</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Filmmaker Spike Lee and entertainer Melba Mooreare among the judges who will select finalists in the 1990 SonyInnovators Awards Program, which honors talented black filmmakersand musicians.   A gala awards ceremony will be held March 15, featuring actressCicely Tyson, guitarist George Benson, dancer Savion Glover and theCount Basie Orchestra.   To help further the careers of winners, Sony provides a cashaward plus a cut crystal trophy designed by the artisans of Hoya.Sony will also feature the 1990 winners in national advertising andpublicity campaigns.   Sponsored by Sony Corporation of America, the Innovators programis in its third year.</TEXT><DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Small, independent theaters are standingup to big cinema chains for first-run movies in Ohio.   Rep. Joan Lawrence has proposed a bill on behalf of independenttheater owners that would require distributors to consider writtenbids from all theaters on first-run films, prohibiting a currentpractice of bidding by telephone, which she says eliminatescompetition.   She said motion picture distributors give the chains firstoption on first runs until after most moviegoers have seen them,and cited the current hit, ``Born on the Fourth of July,'' as anexample.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE></DOC>